# Silver Layer Documentation — Cinema Atlas

## 1. Purpose

This document describes the first version of the Cinema Atlas **silver layer**.

The silver layer takes the raw TMDB JSON stored in the bronze S3 layer and turns it into clean, typed, deduplicated Delta tables. Nested JSON structures (genres, cast, crew, releases, reviews, etc.) are flattened and normalized into dimensions, bridges, and fact tables so the data can be queried and, later, used to build the gold analytics layer.

The silver layer is built from the scoped historical TMDB pull only (movies released 2000–2026 with `vote_count >= 200`). Other sources (IMDb, Wikipedia, Wikidata, MovieLens) may be conformed into silver later; the design leaves room for them but does not include them yet.

---

## 2. Environment and access method

The project runs on **Databricks Free Edition**, which has two constraints that shaped the design:

* Free Edition does not support Unity Catalog **external locations / storage credentials** to a user-owned S3 bucket, so the "IAM role → storage credential → external location" pattern is not available.
* Serverless compute blocks direct Spark access to `s3://` paths (no Hadoop config / instance profile).

Because of this, S3 is accessed the same way the bronze ingestion already worked — with **boto3 and AWS access keys** — but the keys are stored securely instead of hardcoded:

* A dedicated **read-only IAM user** (`databricks-s3-reader`) was created in AWS with a policy granting `s3:GetObject` / `s3:ListBucket` / `s3:GetBucketLocation` on the `de-cinema-atlas-data` bucket only.
* Its access key is stored in a **Databricks secret scope** (`cinema_atlas`), keys `aws_access_key_id` and `aws_secret_access_key`. No credentials appear in the notebook, so it is safe to commit to GitHub.

---

## 3. Pipeline flow

```text
S3 bronze (raw JSON, one file per id)
  → boto3 (keys read from secret scope) downloads files in parallel
  → written as one .jsonl per endpoint into a Databricks managed Volume
        /Volumes/milkmoo/bronze/tmdb_raw/{endpoint}.jsonl
  → Spark reads the Volume (serverless can read managed Volumes)
  → flatten / explode / cast / deduplicate
  → managed Delta tables in milkmoo.silver
```

Serverless Spark cannot read the external S3 bucket directly, but it **can** read a managed Volume, so the Volume acts as the bridge between boto3 and Spark.

The silver tables are **managed Delta tables** in the existing `milkmoo` catalog (`milkmoo.silver` schema). On Free Edition they live in Databricks-managed storage rather than under an `s3://…/silver/` prefix; this is the supported setup for this edition.

